              line-height: 1.4;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Did Trump’s tariff threat start the Canadian political crisis?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">In short, yes and no. Donald Trump's threat to impose 25% tariffs on Canada has pushed Prime Minister Justin Trudeau to the <a href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-21-dec-2024-7" target="_blank">brink of resignation</a>. The prime minister faces mounting domestic and international pressure. Canada's Finance Minister, Chrystia Freeland, left over disagreements with Trudeau on responding to the looming tariff threat. Freeland stressed the need for Canada to prepare for a potential economic confrontation with the US and assert itself against Trump, which Trudeau didn't do. This has led to calls for Trudeau's resignation from all sides of the political spectrum.</p>
        <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">However, Canadian internal politics were complex before Trump's election. Canada has been going through a <a href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-21-dec-2024-8" target="_blank">debt crisis</a> this year with slow economic growth. Things have become more unaffordable for many Canadians, and many have been frustrated with the overall situation. Trudeau had already <a href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-21-dec-2024-9" target="_blank">lost popularity</a> before the US election. The Liberal Party has had internal divisions for a while, and the Conservatives have been <a href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-21-dec-2024-10" target="_blank">polling higher</a> in Canada’s more populous provinces since 2023. This was a long time coming, but Trudeau's recent performance in responding to Trump's tariff threat might have been the last straw.</p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-column>
